# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: business-executive
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] A **board of directors** is a governing body that supervises the activities of a business, a nonprofit organization, or a government agency.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The powers, duties, and responsibilities of a board of directors are determined by government regulations (including the jurisdiction's corporate law) and the organization's own constitution and by-laws.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] These authorities may specify the number of members of the board, how they are to be chosen, and how often they are to meet.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In an organization with voting members, the board is accountable to, and may be subordinate to, the organization's full membership, which usually elect the members of the board.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In a stock corporation, non-executive directors are elected by the shareholders, and the board has ultimate responsibility for the management of the corporation.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In nations with codetermination (such as Germany and Sweden), the workers of a corporation elect a set fraction of the board's members.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The board of directors appoints the chief executive officer of the corporation and sets out the overall strategic direction.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In corporations with dispersed ownership, the identification and nomination of directors (that shareholders vote for or against) are often done by the board itself, leading to a high degree of self-perpetuation.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In a non-stock corporation with no general voting membership, the board is the supreme governing body of the institution, and its members are sometimes chosen by the board itself.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Other names include *board of directors and advisors*, *board of governors*, *board of managers*, *board of regents*, *board of trustees*, and *board of visitors*.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] It may also be called the *executive board*.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The legal responsibilities of boards and board members vary with the nature of the organization, and between jurisdictions.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] For companies with shares publicly listed for negotiation, these responsibilities are typically much more rigorous and complex than for those of other types.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Typically, the board chooses one of its members to be the *chairman* (often now called the "chair" or "chairperson"), who holds whatever title is specified in the by-laws or articles of association.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] However, in membership organizations, the members elect the president of the organization and the president becomes the board chair, unless the by-laws say otherwise.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The directors of an organization are the persons who are members of its board.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Several specific terms categorize directors by the presence or absence of their other relationships to the organization.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Corporations may designate a former senior executive and ex-board member as an honorary board member, a position that does not carry any executive authority but represents recognition of the person's corporate governorship and performance.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] An inside director is a director who is also an employee, officer, chief executive, major shareholder, or someone similarly connected to the organization.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Inside directors represent the interests of the entity's stakeholders, and often have special knowledge of its inner workings, its financial or market position, and so on.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] An inside director who is employed as a manager or executive of the organization is sometimes referred to as an executive director (not to be confused with the title executive director sometimes used for the CEO position in some organizations).
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Executive directors often have a specified area of responsibility in the organization, such as finance, marketing, human resources, or production.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] An outside director is a member of the board who is not otherwise employed by or engaged with the organization, and does not represent any of its stakeholders.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] A typical example is a director who is president of a firm in a different industry.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Outside directors are not employees of the company or affiliated with it in any other way.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Outside directors bring outside experience and perspectives to the board.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] For example, for a company that serves a domestic market only, the presence of CEOs from global multinational corporations as outside directors can help to provide insights on export and import opportunities and international trade options.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] One of the arguments for having outside directors is that they can keep a watchful eye on the inside directors and on the way the organization is run.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Outside directors are unlikely to tolerate "insider dealing" between inside directors, as outside directors do not benefit from the company or organization.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Outside directors are often useful in handling disputes between inside directors, or between shareholders and the board.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] They are thought to be advantageous because they can be objective and present little risk of conflict of interest.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] On the other hand, they might lack familiarity with the specific issues connected to the organization's governance, and they might not know about the industry or sector in which the organization is operating.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Individual directors often serve on more than one board.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This practice results in an interlocking directorate, where a relatively small number of individuals have significant influence over many important entities.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This situation can have important corporate, social, economic, and legal consequences, and has been the subject of significant research.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The science of this process has been slow to develop due to the secretive nature of the way most companies run their boards, however some standardization is beginning to develop.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Some who are pushing for this standardization in the US are the National Association of Corporate Directors, McKinsey and The Board Group.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] A board of directors conducts its meetings according to the rules and procedures contained in its governing documents.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] These procedures may allow the board to conduct its business by conference call or other electronic means.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] They may also specify how a quorum is to be determined.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The responsibilities of a board of directors vary depending on the nature and type of business entity and the laws applying to the entity (see types of business entity).
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] There are numerous types of business entities available throughout the world such as a corporation, limited liability company, cooperative, business trust, partnership, private limited company, and public limited company.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Much of what has been written about boards of directors relates to boards of directors of business entities actively traded on public markets.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] More recently, however, material is becoming available for boards of private and closely held businesses including family businesses.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] A board-only organization is one whose board is self-appointed, rather than being accountable to a base of members through elections; or in which the powers of the membership are extremely limited.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The amount of powers and authority delegated to the board depend on the bylaws and rules of the particular organization.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Some organizations place matters exclusively in the board's control while in others, the general membership retains full power and the board can only make recommendations.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The setup of a board of directors varies widely across organizations and may include provisions that are applicable to corporations, in which the "shareholders" are the members of the organization.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] A difference may be that the membership elects the officers of the organization, such as the president and the secretary, and the officers become members of the board in addition to the directors and retain those duties on the board.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The directors may also be classified as officers in this situation.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] There may also be ex-officio members of the board, or persons who are members due to another position that they hold.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] These ex-officio members have all the same rights as the other board members.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Members of the board may be removed before their term is complete.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Details on how they can be removed are usually provided in the bylaws.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] If the bylaws do not contain such details, the section on disciplinary procedures in *Robert's Rules of Order* may be used.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In a publicly held company, directors are elected to represent and are legally obligated as fiduciaries to represent owners of the company—the shareholders/stockholders.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In this capacity they establish policies and make decisions on issues such as whether there is a dividend and how much it is, stock options distributed to employees, and the hiring/firing and compensation of upper management.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Theoretically, the control of a company is divided between two bodies: the board of directors, and the shareholders in general meeting.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In practice, the amount of power exercised by the board varies with the type of company.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In small private companies, the directors and the shareholders are normally the same people, and thus there is no real division of power.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Another feature of boards of directors in large public companies is that the board tends to have more *de facto* power.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Most shareholders do not attend shareholder meetings, but rather cast proxy votes via mail, phone, or internet, thus allowing the board to vote for them.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] However, proxy votes are not a total delegation of the voting power, as the board must vote the proxy shares as directed by their owner even when it contradicts the board's views.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In addition, many shareholders vote to accept all recommendations of the board rather than try to get involved in management, since each shareholder's power, as well as interest and information is so small.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Larger institutional investors also grant the board proxies.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The large number of shareholders also makes it hard for them to organize.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] However, there have been moves recently to try to increase shareholder activism among both institutional investors and individuals with small shareholdings.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] A contrasting view is that in large public companies it is upper management and not boards that wield practical power, because boards delegate nearly all of their power to the top executive employees, adopting their recommendations almost without fail.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] As a practical matter, executives even choose the directors, with shareholders normally following management recommendations and voting for them.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In most cases, serving on a board is not a career unto itself.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] For major corporations, the board members are usually professionals or leaders in their field.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In the case of outside directors, they are often senior leaders of other organizations.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Nevertheless, board members often receive remunerations amounting to hundreds of thousands of dollars per year since they often sit on the boards of several companies.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Inside directors are usually not paid for sitting on a board, but the duty is instead considered part of their larger job description.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Outside directors are usually paid for their services.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] These remunerations vary between corporations, but usually consist of a yearly or monthly salary, additional compensation for each meeting attended, stock options, and various other benefits. such as travel, hotel and meal expenses for the board meetings.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Academic research has identified different types of board directors.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Their characteristics and experiences shape their role and performance.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] For instance, directors with multiple mandates are often referred to as busy directors.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Their monitoring performance is considered to be comparatively weak due to the limited time they can dedicate to this task.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Overconfident directors are found to pay higher premiums in corporate acquisitions and make worse takeover choices.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Locally rooted directors tend to be overrepresented and lack international experience, which can lead to lower valuations, especially in internationally oriented firms.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Directors' military experience is associated with rigorous monitoring and improved corporate governance.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In some European and Asian countries, there are two separate boards, an executive board (or management board) for day-to-day business and a supervisory board (elected by the shareholders and employees) for supervising the executive board.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In these countries, the chairman of the supervisory board is equivalent to the chairman of a single-tier board, while the chairman of the management board is reckoned as the company's CEO or managing director.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] These two roles are always held by different people.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This ensures a distinction between management by the executive board and governance by the supervisory board and allows for clear lines of authority.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The aim is to prevent a conflict of interest and too much power being concentrated in the hands of one person.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] There is a strong parallel here with the structure of government, where parliament (the supervisory board) oversees a cabinet of ministers (management officials, comprising the executive board) led by a head of government (CEO).
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Board structures and procedures vary both within and among OECD countries.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Some countries have two-tier boards that separate the supervisory function and the management function into different bodies.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Such systems typically have a "supervisory board" composed of nonexecutive board members and a "management board" composed entirely of executives.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Other countries have "unitary" boards, which bring together executive and non-executive board members.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In some countries there is also an additional statutory body for audit purposes.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The OECD Principles are intended to be sufficiently general to apply to whatever board structure is charged with the functions of governing the enterprise and monitoring management.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The development of a separate board of directors to manage/govern/oversee a company has occurred incrementally and indefinitely over legal history.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Until the end of the 19th century, it seems to have been generally assumed that the general meeting (of all shareholders) was the supreme organ of a company, and that the board of directors merely acted as an agent of the company subject to the control of the shareholders in general meeting.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The new approach did not secure immediate approval, but it was endorsed by the House of Lords in *Quin & Axtens v Salmon* [1909] AC 442 and has since received general acceptance.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Under English law, successive versions of Table A have reinforced the norm that, unless the directors are acting contrary to the law or the provisions of the Articles, the powers of conducting the management and affairs of the company are vested in them.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] It has been remarked that this development in the law was somewhat surprising at the time, as the relevant provisions in Table A (as it was then) seemed to contradict this approach rather than to endorse it.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The age of board members has become a notable trend across global stock exchanges, reflecting an increasingly older demographic in leadership roles.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] As of 2025, the average age of board members of companies listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange stands at 62.2 years, while the United Kingdom reports an average of 60.1 years, Germany 59.3 years, South Korea 59 years, and Hong Kong 54.9 years.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] New York Stock Exchange companies exhibit the highest average age, at 62.9 years.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In response to this aging trend, some firms, particularly those in entertainment and trend-driven sectors, have actively sought to appoint younger board members.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] An example is Sanrio, the Japanese company behind the Hello Kitty franchise, which reduced the average age of its board from 68 years in 2020 to 51 years by 2024, signaling a deliberate intergenerational shift in governance.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In most legal systems, the appointment and removal of directors is voted upon by the shareholders in general meeting or through a proxy statement.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] For publicly traded companies in the U.S., the directors which are available to vote on are largely selected by either the board as a whole or a nominating committee.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Shareholder nominations can only occur at the general meeting itself or through the prohibitively expensive process of mailing out ballots separately; in May 2009 the SEC proposed a new rule allowing shareholders meeting certain criteria to add nominees to the proxy statement.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In countries with co-determination, a fixed fraction of the board is elected by the corporation's workers.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Directors may also leave office by resignation or death.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In some legal systems, directors may also be removed by a resolution of the remaining directors (in some countries they may only do so "with cause"; in others the power is unrestricted).
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Some jurisdictions also permit the board of directors to appoint directors, either to fill a vacancy which arises on resignation or death, or as an addition to the existing directors.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In practice, it can be quite difficult to remove a director by a resolution in general meeting.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In many legal systems, the director has a right to receive special notice of any resolution to remove them; the company must often supply a copy of the proposal to the director, who is usually entitled to be heard by the meeting.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The director may require the company to circulate any representations that they wish to make.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Furthermore, the director's contract of service will usually entitle them to compensation if they are removed, and may often include a generous "golden parachute" which also acts as a deterrent to removal.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] A 2010 study examined how corporate shareholders voted in director elections in the United States.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] It found that directors received fewer votes from shareholders when their companies performed poorly, had excess CEO compensation, or had poor shareholder protection.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Also, directors received fewer votes when they did not regularly attend board meetings or received negative recommendations from a proxy advisory firm.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The study also shows that companies often improve their corporate governance by removing poison pills or classified boards and by reducing excessive CEO pay after their directors receive low shareholder support.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Board accountability to shareholders is a recurring issue.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In September 2010, *The New York Times* noted that several directors who had overseen companies which had failed in the 2008 financial crisis had found new positions as directors.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The SEC sometimes imposes a ban (a "D&O bar") on serving on a board as part of its fraud cases, and one of these was upheld in 2013.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The exercise by the board of directors of its powers usually occurs in board meetings.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Most legal systems require sufficient notice to be given to all directors of these meetings, and that a quorum must be present before any business may be conducted.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In most common law countries, the powers of the board are vested in the board as a whole, and not in the individual directors.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] However, in instances an individual director may still bind the company by their acts by virtue of their ostensible authority (see also: the rule in *Turquand's Case*).
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Because directors exercise control and management over the organization, but organizations are (in theory) run for the benefit of the shareholders, the law imposes strict duties on directors in relation to the exercise of their duties.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The duties imposed on directors are fiduciary duties, similar to those that the law imposes on those in similar positions of trust: agents and trustees.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The duties apply to each director separately, while the powers apply to the board jointly.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Also, the duties are owed to the company itself, and not to any other entity.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This does not mean that directors can never stand in a fiduciary relationship to the individual shareholders; they may well have such a duty in certain circumstances.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Directors must exercise their powers for a proper purpose.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] While in many instances an improper purpose is readily evident, such as a director looking to enrich themselves or divert an investment opportunity to a relative, such breaches usually involve a breach of the director's duty to act in good faith.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Greater difficulties arise where the director, while acting in good faith, is serving a purpose that is not regarded by the law as proper.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The seminal authority in the United Kingdom in relation to what amounts to a proper purpose is the Supreme Court decision in Eclairs Group Ltd v JKX Oil & Gas plc (2015).
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The case concerned the powers of directors under the articles of association of the company to disenfranchise voting rights attached to shares for failure to properly comply with notice served on the shareholders.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Prior to that case the leading authority was *Howard Smith Ltd v Ampol Ltd* [1974] AC 821.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The case concerned the power of the directors to issue new shares.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] It was alleged that the directors had issued many new shares purely to deprive a particular shareholder of his voting majority.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] If so, the mere fact that an incidental result (even if it was a desired consequence) was that a shareholder lost their majority, or a takeover bid was defeated, this would not itself make the share issue improper.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] But if the sole purpose was to destroy a voting majority, or block a takeover bid, that would be an improper purpose.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Not all jurisdictions recognised the "proper purpose" duty as separate from the "good faith" duty however.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Directors cannot, without the consent of the company, fetter their discretion in relation to the exercise of their powers, and cannot bind themselves to vote in a particular way at future board meetings.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This is so even if there is no improper motive or purpose, and no personal advantage to the director.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This does not mean, however, that the board cannot agree to the company entering into a contract which binds the company to a certain course, even if certain actions in that course will require further board approval, such as issuing bonds.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The company remains bound, but the directors retain the discretion to vote against taking the future actions (although that may involve a breach by the company of the contract that the board previously approved).
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] As fiduciaries, the directors may not put themselves in a position where their interests and duties conflict with the duties that they owe to the company.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The law takes the view that good faith must not only be done, but must be manifestly seen to be done, and zealously patrols the conduct of directors in this regard; and will not allow directors to escape liability by asserting that their decisions were in fact well founded.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] By definition, where a director enters into a transaction with a company, there is a conflict between the director's interest (to enrich themselves with the transaction) and their duty to the company (to ensure that the company gets as much as it can out of the transaction).
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In some places, this rule is so strictly enforced that, even where the conflict of interest or conflict of duty is purely hypothetical, the directors can be forced to disgorge all personal gains arising from it.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] "A corporate body can only act by agents, and it is, of course, the duty of those agents so to act as best to promote the interests of the corporation whose affairs they are conducting.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Such agents have duties to discharge of a fiduciary nature towards their principal.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] , with the interests of those whom he is bound to protect...
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] However, in many jurisdictions the members of the company are permitted to ratify transactions which would otherwise fall foul of this principle.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] It is also largely accepted in most jurisdictions that this principle can be overridden in the company's constitution.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] In many countries, there is also a statutory duty to declare interests in relation to any transactions, and the director can be fined for failing to make disclosure.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Directors must not, without the informed consent of the company, use for their own profit the company's assets, opportunities, or information.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This prohibition is much less flexible than the prohibition against the transactions with the company, and attempts to circumvent it using provisions in the articles have met with limited success.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] And accordingly, the directors were required to disgorge the profits that they made, and the shareholders received their windfall.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The decision has been followed in several subsequent cases, and is now regarded as settled law.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Directors cannot compete directly with the company without a conflict of interest arising.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Similarly, they should not act as directors of competing companies, as their duties to each company would then conflict with each other.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Traditionally, the level of care and skill which has to be demonstrated by a director has been framed largely with reference to the non-executive director.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] However, a more modern approach has since developed, and in *Dorchester Finance Co Ltd v Stebbing* [1989] BCLC 498 the court held that the rule in *Equitable Fire* related only to skill, and not to diligence.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This was a dual subjective and objective test, and one deliberately pitched at a higher level.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] More recently, it has been suggested that both the tests of skill and diligence should be assessed objectively and subjectively; in the United Kingdom, the statutory provisions relating to directors' duties in the new Companies Act 2006 have been codified on this basis.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Historically, directors' duties have been owed almost exclusively to the company and its members, and the board was expected to exercise its powers for the financial benefit of the company.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] However, more recently there have been attempts to "soften" the position, and provide for more scope for directors to act as good corporate citizens.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This represents a considerable departure from the traditional notion that directors' duties are owed only to the company.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The changes have therefore been the subject of some criticism.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The adoption of technology that facilitates the meeting preparation and execution of directors continues to grow.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Board directors are increasingly leveraging this technology to communicate and collaborate within a secure environment to access meeting materials, communicate with each other, and execute their governance responsibilities.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This trend is particularly acute in the United States where a robust market of early adopters garnered acceptance of board software by organizations resulting in higher penetration of the board portal services in the region.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Most companies have weak mechanisms for bringing the voice of society into the board room.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] They rely on personalities who were not appointed for their understanding of societal issues.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Often they give limited focus (both through time and financial resource) to issues of corporate responsibility and sustainability.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] A social board has society designed into its structure.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] It elevates the voice of society through specialist appointments to the board and mechanisms that empower innovation from within the organisation.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Social boards align themselves with themes that are important to society.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] These may include measuring worker pay ratios, linking personal social and environmental objectives to remuneration, integrated reporting, fair tax and B-Corp certification.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Social boards recognise that they are part of society and that they require more than a licence to operate to succeed.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] They balance short-term shareholder pressure against long-term value creation, managing the business for a plurality of stakeholders including employees, shareholders, supply chains and civil society.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] India has no legislative equivalent to Sarbanes–Oxley Act (given below), though Clause 49 of the SEBI Listing Agreement provides relevant rules.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] India adopted this new corporate governance standard under Article 49 of the Listing Agreement on 31 December 2005, which is mandatory for all listed companies.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] This provision mandates certain governance practices for companies listed on Indian stock exchanges.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Key provisions under clause 49 include those under which top executives like CEOs and CFOs must verify the effectiveness and accuracy of financial statements.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] After the Satyam scandal in 2009, internal financial controls gained importance in India.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The Companies Act, 2013 introduced internal financial controls imposing specific responsibilities on the board, audit committee, management and others.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The Sarbanes–Oxley Act of 2002 has introduced new standards of accountability on boards of U.S. companies or companies listed on U.S. stock exchanges.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Under the act, directors risk large fines and prison sentences in the case of accounting crimes.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Internal control is now the direct responsibility of directors.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The vast majority of companies covered by the act have hired internal auditors to ensure that the company adheres to required standards of internal control.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The internal auditors are required by law to report directly to an audit board, consisting of directors more than half of whom are outside directors, one of whom is a "financial expert".
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The law requires companies listed on the major stock exchanges (NYSE, NASDAQ) to have a majority of independent directors—directors who are not otherwise employed by the firm or in a business relationship with it.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] According to the Corporate Library's study, the average size of publicly traded company's board is 9.2 members, and most boards range from 3 to 31 members.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] According to Investopedia, some analysts think the ideal size is seven.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] State law may specify a minimum number of directors, maximum number of directors, and qualifications for directors (e.g. whether board members must be individuals or may be business entities).
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] While a board may have several committees, two—the compensation committee and audit committee—are critical and must be made up of at least three independent directors and no inside directors.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Other common committees in boards are nominating, governance and investment.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Directors of Fortune 500 companies received median pay of $234,000 in 2011.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] A 2011 study by the National Association of Corporate Directors in the United States estimated that directors averaged 4.3 hours a week on board work.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Surveys have indicated that about 20% of nonprofit foundations pay their board members, and 2% of American nonprofit organizations do.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] 80% of nonprofit organizations require board members to personally contribute to the organization.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] As of 2007, this percentage had increased in recent years.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] According to John Gillespie, a former investment banker and co-author of a book critical of boards, "Far too much of their time has been for check-the-box and cover-your-behind activities rather than real monitoring of executives and providing strategic advice on behalf of shareholders".
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] At the same time, scholars have found that individual directors have a large effect on major corporate initiatives such as mergers and acquisitions and cross-border investments.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] According to the International Institute of Management, the rise in investor dissatisfaction, class-action lawsuits and shareholder activism has resulted in more attention directed toward the board of directors and the lack of corporate governance accountability.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Shareholders' complaints include issues such as excessive executive compensation and passive participation (lack of proper governance) of the board members.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The journal paper cites examples of underperforming CEOs of Fortune 500 companies who took compensation and retirement package in hundreds of millions of dollars while the stock price of their companies lost billions of dollars.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The research proposes institutionalizing a standardized board evaluation framework to help balance between the executive compensation and protecting the interest of shareholders.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] The issue of gender representation on corporate boards of directors has been the subject of much criticism in recent years.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] Governments and corporations have responded with measures such as legislation mandating gender quotas and comply or explain systems to address the disproportionality of gender representation on corporate boards.
[src:business-executive/board-of-director] A study of the French corporate elite has found that certain social classes are also disproportionately represented on boards, with those from the upper and, especially, upper-middle classes tending to dominate.
[src:business-executive/budget] A **budget** is a calculation plan, usually but not always financial, for a defined period, often one year or a month.
[src:business-executive/budget] A budget may include anticipated sales volumes and revenues, resource quantities including time, costs and expenses, environmental impacts such as greenhouse gas emissions, other impacts, assets, liabilities and cash flows.
[src:business-executive/budget] Companies, governments, families, and other organizations use budgets to express strategic plans of activities in measurable terms.
[src:business-executive/budget] Preparing a budget allows companies, authorities, private entities or families to establish priorities and evaluate the achievement of their objectives.
[src:business-executive/budget] To achieve these goals it may be necessary to incur a deficit (expenses exceed income) or, on the contrary, it may be possible to save, in which case the budget will present a surplus (income exceed expenses).
[src:business-executive/budget] In the field of commerce, a budget is also a financial document or report that details the cost that a service will have if performed.
[src:business-executive/budget] Whoever makes the budget must adhere to it and cannot change it if the client accepts the service.
[src:business-executive/budget] A budget expresses intended expenditures along with proposals for how to meet them with resources.
[src:business-executive/budget] A budget may express a surplus, providing resources for use at a future time, or a deficit in which expenditures exceed income or other resources.
[src:business-executive/budget] The budget of a government is a summary or plan of the anticipated resources (often but not always from taxes) and expenditures of that government.
[src:business-executive/budget] There are three types of government budgets: the operating or current budget, the capital or investment budget, and the cash or cash flow budget.
[src:business-executive/budget] The federal budget is prepared by the Office of Management and Budget, and submitted to Congress for consideration.
[src:business-executive/budget] Invariably, Congress makes many and substantial changes.
[src:business-executive/budget] Nearly all American states are required to have balanced budgets, but the federal government is allowed to run deficits.
[src:business-executive/budget] The budget is prepared by the Budget Division Department of Economic Affairs of the Ministry of Finance annually.
[src:business-executive/budget] The Finance Minister is the head of the budget making committee.
[src:business-executive/budget] The present Indian Finance minister is Nirmala Sitharaman.
[src:business-executive/budget] The Budget includes supplementary excess grants and when a proclamation by the President as to failure of Constitutional machinery is in operation in relation to a State or a Union Territory, preparation of the Budget of such State.
[src:business-executive/budget] The first budget of India was submitted on 18 February 1860 by James Wilson.
[src:business-executive/budget] P C Mahalanobis is known as the father of Indian budget.
[src:business-executive/budget] The Philippine budget is considered the most complicated in the world, incorporating multiple approaches in one single budget system: line-item (budget execution), performance (budget accountability), and zero-based budgeting.
[src:business-executive/budget] The Department of Budget and Management (DBM) prepares the National Expenditure Program and forwards it to the Committee on Appropriations of the House of Representatives to come up with a General Appropriations Bill (GAB).
[src:business-executive/budget] The GAB will go through budget deliberations and voting; the same process occurs when the GAB is transmitted to the Philippine Senate.
[src:business-executive/budget] After both houses of Congress approves the GAB, the President signs the bill into a General Appropriations Act (GAA); also, the President may opt to veto the GAB and have it returned to the legislative branch or leave the bill unsigned for 30 days and lapse into law.
[src:business-executive/budget] There are two types of budget bill veto: the line-item veto and the veto of the whole budget.
[src:business-executive/budget] A personal budget or home budget is a finance plan that allocates future personal income towards expenses, savings and debt repayment.
[src:business-executive/budget] Past spending and personal debt are considered when creating a personal budget.
[src:business-executive/budget] There are several methods and tools available for creating, using, and adjusting a personal budget.
[src:business-executive/budget] For example, jobs are an income source, while bills and rent payments are expenses.
[src:business-executive/budget] A third category (other than income and expenses) may be assets (such as property, investments, or other savings or value) representing a potential reserve for funds in case of budget shortfalls.
[src:business-executive/budget] The budget of a business, division, or corporation is a financial forecast for the near-term future, usually the next accounting period, aggregating the expected revenues and expenses of the various departments – operations, human resources, IT, etc.
[src:business-executive/budget] It is thus a key element in integrated business planning, with measurable targets correspondingly devolved to departmental managers (and becoming KPIs); budgets may then also specify non-cash resources, such as staff or time.
[src:business-executive/budget] The budgeting process requires considerable effort, often involving dozens of staff; final sign-off resides with both the financial director and operations director.
[src:business-executive/budget] The responsibility usually sits within the company's financial management area in general, sometimes, specifically in "FP&A".
[src:business-executive/budget] Professionals employed in this role are often designated "**Budget Analyst**", a specialized financial analyst function.
[src:business-executive/budget] Organisations may produce functional budgets, relating to activities, and / or cash budgets, focused on receipts and payments.
[src:business-executive/budget] Incremental budgeting starts with the budget from the previous period, while under zero-based budgeting activities/costs are included only if justified.
[src:business-executive/budget] Under all approaches expected sales or revenue, is typically the starting point; this will be based on the business' planning for the period in question.
[src:business-executive/budget] Directly related elements and costs are typically linked to these (activity based costing may be employed).
[src:business-executive/budget] Support and management functions may be revisited, and the resultant "fixed" costs, such as rent and payroll, will be adjusted - at a minimum for inflation.
[src:business-executive/budget] Capital expenditure, both new investments and maintenance, may be budgeted separately; debt servicing and repayments likewise.
[src:business-executive/budget] See Financial forecast, Cash flow forecast, Financial modeling § Accounting.
[src:business-executive/budget] Whereas the budget is typically compiled on an annual basis - although, e.g. in mining, this may be quarterly - the monitoring is ongoing, with financial and operational adjustments (or interventions) made as warranted; see Financial risk management § Corporate finance for further discussion.
[src:business-executive/budget] Here, if the actual figures delivered come close to those budgeted, this suggests that managers understand their business and have been successful in delivering.
[src:business-executive/budget] On the other hand, if the figures diverge this sends an "out of control" signal; additionally, the share price could suffer where these figures have been communicated to analysts.
[src:business-executive/budget] Criticism is sometimes directed at the nature of budgeting, and its impact on the organization.
[src:business-executive/budget] A second observation is that managers' thinking may emphasize short term, operational thinking at the expense of a long term and strategic perspective, particularly when bonus payments are linked to budget.
[src:business-executive/budget] See Strategic planning § Strategic planning vs. financial planning.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] A **convention** (or **event**), in the sense of a meeting, is a gathering of individuals who meet at an arranged place and time in order to discuss or engage in some common interest.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The most common conventions are based upon industry, profession, and fandom.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Trade conventions typically focus on a particular industry or industry segment, and feature keynote speakers, vendor displays, and other information and activities of interest to the event organizers and attendees.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Professional conventions focus on issues of concern along with advancements related to the profession.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Such conventions are generally organized by societies or communities dedicated to promotion of the topic of interest.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Fan conventions usually feature displays, shows, and sales based on pop culture and guest celebrities.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Science fiction conventions traditionally partake of the nature of both professional conventions and fan conventions, with the balance varying from one to another.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Conventions also exist for various hobbies, such as gaming or model railroads.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Conventions are often planned and coordinated, often in exacting detail, by professional meeting and convention planners, either by staff of the convention's hosting company or by outside specialists.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Most large cities will have a convention center dedicated to hosting such events.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The term MICE (Meetings, Incentives, Conferencing, Exhibitions) is widely used in Asia as a description of the industry.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The Convention ("C") is one of the most dynamic elements in the M.I.C.E. segment.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The industry is generally regulated under the tourism sector.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] In the technical sense, a convention is a meeting of delegates or representatives.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The 1947 Newfoundland National Convention is a classic example of a state-sponsored political convention.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] More often, organizations made up of smaller units, chapters, or lodges, such as labor unions, honorary societies, and fraternities and sororities, meet as a whole in convention by sending delegates of the units to deliberate on the organization's common issues.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] This also applies to a political convention, though in modern times the common issues are limited to selecting a party candidate or party chairman.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] In this technical sense, a congress, when it consists of representatives, is a convention.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The British House of Commons is a convention, as are most other houses of a modern representative legislature.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The National Convention or just "Convention" in France comprised the constitutional and legislative assembly which sat from September 20, 1792, to October 26, 1795.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The governing bodies of religious groups may also be called conventions, such as the General Convention of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America and the Southern Baptist Convention.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Conventions in general enjoy a long history and rich tradition within the United States due in part to their epistemic, moral, and transformative nature.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] So much so that they have been stitched into the fabric of American government.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] As such, they are subject to the rights of the People to enjoy free of governmental interference of any kind.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Throughout the history of the United States, conventions have served as a mechanism of self-governance, providing a vehicle to secure public rights through constitutions, or as a mechanism of redress to amend them.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] In fact, they have been instrumental to the nation's continued development into the representative democracy it is today.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] During the Confederation period under the Articles of Confederation, the former British colonies of North America had united to form a wartime confederation of states.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] One characterized by *state representation* in a weak and decentralized central government headed by the unicameral Congress of the Confederation, the precursor to the modern-day United States Senate.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] One convention of particular note during this time was held between September 11–14, 1786 in Annapolis, Maryland.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The Annapolis Convention, was convened primarily to address issues of commerce between the states, but the agenda quickly became focused upon a wide range of deficiencies posed by the current frame of government.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The convention ended with a resolution by Alexander Hamilton calling for a convention to amend the Articles of Confederation.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Following Hamilton's suggestion, the Confederate Congress called a convention "to render the constitution … adequate to the exigencies of the Union." The Philadelphia Convention begin on May 14, 1787, and ended on September 17, with a proposal for a new Constitution for the union.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Collectively, these conventions directly led to the Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution securing a woman's right to vote.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The Colored Conventions Movement was a series of national, regional, and state conventions held irregularly during the decades preceding and following the American Civil War.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] These conventions offered opportunities for free-born and formerly enslaved African Americans to organize and strategize for racial justice.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] These early conventions argued for the abolition of slavery, equal educational opportunities, land reform, and the merits of emigration out of the United States.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Prior to the ratification of the United States Constitution, a convention of independent states would hold sovereign power over the Confederate Congress.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] However, most of these conventions were called by state legislatures to resolve boundary disputes; others were called for economic purposes; such as was the case with the Annapolis Convention that ultimately led to the framing of the Constitution.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Since ratification however, it has become widely understood that the Constitution recognizes the authority of states and state legislatures to appoint commissioners to these types of conventions.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Although any agreements they may reach are subject to Congressional approval under the Commerce Clause.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Examples of this form of convention include the Yellowstone River Compact Commission, Red River Compact Commission, Colorado River Compact, and the Delaware River Basin Commission.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Interstate conventions, *otherwise known as conventions of states*, may be called by the Governor as well, such was the case with a series of meetings from December 15, 1814, to January 5, 1815, collectively known as the Hartford Convention.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The convention was called to address the ongoing War of 1812, as well as, an array of problems arising from the growth of the federal government.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Single state conventions may be called due to a provision of the state's constitution, by referendum, or in response to amendment proposal from Congress.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] To date, there have been 233 state-level conventions in the history of the United States, all of which convened to revise or even entirely rewrite their state constitutions.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] In each and everyone of these convention, delegates were elected to the Convention.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Conventions are ubiquitous in the corporate sector and include the State Conventions of the National Association of Realtors and the Annual Convention for the Cleaning Equipment Trade Association for just two of countless examples.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Presidential nominating conventions are called by political parties in the United States.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] They have been a permanent feature of the government since its founding.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] After the Civil War, Congress passed the Reconstruction Acts, resulting in the states that once comprised the Confederate States of America being divided into military districts.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] These Acts of Congress mandated that the rebel states revise their constitutions by means of conventions of elected delegates, to include the ratification of the thirteenth, fourteenth, and fifteenth amendments to the United States Constitution.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Congress has also frequently employed conventions for the admission of new states to the Union under Article Four of the United States Constitution.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] In all, a total of thirty-one states were admitted to the union in this manner.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Under Article Five, Congress is *obligated* to call such a convention when thirty-four states have formally submitted to Congress, a joint resolution known as a state application.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] To date, the Clerk of the United States House of Representatives has identified nearly two hundred of these applications.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Yet, this method of proposal remains elusive and has never occurred in the history of the United States.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Article Five also provides that Congress may choose among two modes of ratification, either by means of state legislatures or by state conventions.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] To date the state convention ratification mode was used by Congress just once, to ratify the Twenty-first Amendment to the United States Constitution which ended prohibition.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] As a result, many states have statutory provisions providing for the elections of delegates for future ratification conventions.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The Delegates of the Philadelphia Convention chose state conventions instead of state legislatures as the bodies to consider ratification of the Constitution.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] The Constitution was eventually adopted per the provisions of Article Seven as the Supreme Law of the Land through a series of Ratification Conventions that ultimately culminated on May 29, 1790, with the final ratification which was provided by the State of Rhode Island.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Despite this long history of conventions in the United States dating back well before the ratification of the Constitution, confusion and controversy has emerged in recent decades.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Perhaps, most prominent among them is the distinction between what constitutes a state convention and what constitutes a federal convention.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Fortunately this can be determined by identification of the convening authority.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] A federal convention is one called and convened for the purpose of exercising a federal function under authority deriving directly from the United States Constitution.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Conversely, state legislatures only exercise federal functions when they apply to Congress for a convention to propose amendments or when they call a convention to ratify a proposed amendment submitted to the states by Congress.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Otherwise conventions called and convened under authority deriving directly from a state's constitution, are limited to addressing the constitutional matters of that particular state alone.
[src:business-executive/business-conference] Nearly all of the sovereign states do not yet have statutory provisions for conventions beyond their permanent legislature, state amendatory conventions , and conventions for *ratification* of proposals to amend the Constitution .
[src:business-executive/business-conference] There are no state laws explicitly providing for the election of delegates for a convention to propose amendments to the Constitution.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] A **business executive** is a person responsible for running an organization, although the exact nature of the role varies depending on the organization.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Executives run companies or government agencies.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They create plans to help their organizations grow.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Becoming an executive usually takes years of promotions and hard work since the qualifications of this role needs hard working individuals with years of experience in multiple facets of the business.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] The business executive occupation covers many jobs.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] These positions include chief executive officer, department store manager, and small business operator.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Executives are in charge of their organization.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They create and review goals for the company.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They work closely with a team of upper-level staff or assistants.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] This team may make both long- and short-range plans to achieve these goals.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Once the plans are set, executives make sure the company follows the changes.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They do this by meeting with the managers of all the departments and getting progress reports.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Executives are typically elected by the organization's owners, shareholders, and board of directors.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] The term usually refers to the person running the organization or someone involved in the upper-level management role of a corporation, company, as opposed to being the founder, owner, or majority shareholder of the organization.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Executives' duties depend on how many people are on their staff.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Some executives oversee general managers in different areas.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] In larger organizations, they may direct one area, such as marketing, finance, or legal services.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] For example, in the financial area, executives may direct the buying or selling of land or other investments.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They may direct staff on what tasks need to be done.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They may choose computer systems to record data, such as budgets.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] When complaints arise, executives may direct investigations to resolve what occurred in the agency or between staff members.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] A large part of an executive's job is developing relationships with people outside the organization.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] These people may be customers or contributors.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] One way executives create relationships is by giving speeches at conferences.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Executives may also serve on the boards of community groups.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] These activities promote the company and its leader.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] In addition, executives oversee budgets.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They use budgets to analyze how well the organization is running.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They make suggestions about where to cut expenses.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Executives may also suggest where improvements could be made.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Executives also negotiate contracts with outside agencies.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They need good persuasion skills to keep costs down.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Government executives oversee agencies that develop laws and regulations.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They meet regularly with their citizens.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They learn how voters feel about the issues.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Officials need to do these reality checks to see if they have the citizens' support.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Executives also promote economic growth within their communities.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They plan and organize different activities to help meet these goals.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Government executives make connections between the United States and other countries.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They help to promote international trade.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] The government executive occupation also covers many jobs.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] They range from city council member, mayor, and governor, all the way up to President or head of state.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Other officials are appointed to their jobs.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] In smaller communities, many of these jobs may be volunteer positions.
[src:business-executive/business-executive] Sometimes these jobs run through only part of the year.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] A **chief executive officer** (**CEO**), also known as a **chief executive** or **managing director**, is the top-ranking corporate officer charged with the management of a company or a nonprofit organization.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] CEOs find roles in various organizations, including public and private corporations, nonprofit organizations, and even some government organizations (notably state-owned enterprises).
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The governor and CEO of a corporation or company typically report to the board of directors and are charged with maximizing the value of the business, which may include maximizing the profitability, market share, revenue, or another financial metric.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In the nonprofit and government sector, CEOs typically aim at achieving outcomes related to the organization's mission, usually provided by legislation.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] CEOs are also frequently assigned the role of the main manager of the organization and the highest-ranking officer in the C-suite.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The term "chief executive officer" is attested as early as 1782, when an ordinance of the Congress of the Confederation of the United States of America used the term to refer to governors and other leaders of the executive branches of each of the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In draft additions to the *Oxford English Dictionary* published online in 2011, the *Dictionary* says that the use of "CEO" as an acronym for a chief executive officer originated in Australia, with the first attestation being in 1914.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The first American usage cited is from 1972.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The responsibilities of an organization's CEO are set by the organization's board of directors or other authority, depending on the organization's structure.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] They can be far-reaching or quite limited, and are typically enshrined in a formal delegation of authority regarding business administration.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Typically, responsibilities include being an active decision-maker on business strategy and other key policy issues, as well as leader, manager, and executor roles.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The communicator role can involve speaking to the press and the public, as well as to the organization's management and employees.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The decision-making role entails making high-level decisions regarding policy and strategy.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The CEO is responsible for implementing the goals, targets, and strategic objectives as determined by the board of directors.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] As an executive officer of the company, the CEO reports the status of the business to the board of directors, motivates employees, and drives change within the organization.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] As a manager, the CEO presides over the organization's day-to-day operations.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The CEO is the person who is ultimately accountable for a company's business decisions, including those in operations, marketing, business development, finance, human resources, etc.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The CEO of a political party is often entrusted with fundraising, particularly for election campaigns.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The use of the CEO title may be used by for-profit companies or non-profit or charitable organisations, such as the Wikimedia Foundation.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In some countries, there is a dual board system with two separate boards, one executive board for the day-to-day business and one supervisory board for control purposes (selected by the shareholders).
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In these countries, the CEO presides over the executive board and the chairperson presides over the supervisory board, and these two roles will always be held by different people.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] This ensures a distinction between management by the executive board and governance by the supervisory board.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] This allows for clear lines of authority.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In the United States, the board of directors (elected by the shareholders) is often equivalent to the supervisory board, while the executive board may often be known as the executive committee (the division/subsidiary heads and C-level officers that report directly to the CEO).
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In the United States, and in business, the executive officers are usually the top officers of a corporation, the chief executive officer (CEO) being the best-known type.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The definition varies; for instance, the California Corporate Disclosure Act defines "executive officers" as the five most highly compensated officers not also sitting on the board of directors.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In the case of a sole proprietorship, an executive officer is the sole proprietor.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In the case of a partnership, an executive officer is a managing partner, senior partner, or administrative partner.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In the case of a limited liability company, an executive officer is any member, manager, or officer.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Depending on the organization, a CEO may have several subordinate executives to help run the day-to-day administration of the company, each of whom has specific functional responsibilities referred to as senior executives, executive officers, or corporate officers.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Subordinate executives are given different titles in different organizations, but one common category of subordinate executive, if the CEO is also the president, is the vice president (VP).
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] An organization may have more than one vice president, each tasked with a different area of responsibility (e.g., VP of finance, VP of human resources).
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Examples of subordinate executive officers who typically report to the CEO include the chief operating officer (COO), chief financial officer (CFO), chief strategy officer (CSO), chief marketing officer (CMO), and chief business officer (CBO).
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In the US, the term "chief executive officer" is used primarily in business, whereas the term "executive director" is used primarily in the not-for-profit sector.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] These terms are generally mutually exclusive and refer to distinct legal duties and responsibilities.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The CEO is the highest-ranking executive in a company, making corporate decisions, managing operations, allocating resources, and serving as the main point of communication between the board of directors and the company.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In the UK, chief executive and chief executive officer are used in local government, where their position in law is described as the "head of paid service", and in business and in the charitable sector.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] As of 2013, the use of the term director for senior charity staff is deprecated to avoid confusion with the legal duties and responsibilities associated with being a charity director or trustee, which are normally non-executive (unpaid) roles.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The term **managing director** is often used in lieu of chief executive officer.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Business publicists since the days of Edward Bernays (1891–1995) and his client John D.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Rockefeller (1839–1937) and even more successfully the corporate publicists for Henry Ford, promoted the concept of the "celebrity CEO".
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Business journalists have often adopted this approach, which assumes that the corporate achievements, especially in the arena of manufacturing, are produced by uniquely talented individuals, especially the "heroic CEO".
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In effect, journalists celebrate a CEO who takes distinctive strategic actions.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The model is the celebrity in entertainment, sports, and politics – compare the "great man theory".
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Journalism thereby exaggerates the importance of the CEO and tends to neglect harder-to-describe broader corporate factors.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] There is little attention to the intricately organized technical bureaucracy that actually does the work.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Hubris sets in when the CEO internalizes the celebrity and becomes excessively self-confident in making complex decisions.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] There may be an emphasis on the sort of decisions that attract the celebrity journalists.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Research published in 2009 by Ulrike Malmendier and Geoffrey Tate indicates that "firms with award-winning CEOs subsequently underperform, in terms both of stock and of operating performance".
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] CEOs and senior executives are governed by the board of directors.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The proper selection and evaluation of the CEO and the executive team is critical to the company’s performance.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Yet there is no established standard framework to evaluate and govern the CEO performance.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] One initiative proposes a standardized questionnaire used in annual CEO reviews and senior executive recruitment.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] These questionnaires help guide CEO strategy and assure the shareholders that the company and its executive team are on the right track.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Every CEO and C-level executive must be able to provide specific answers to the preceding questions, readily and clearly.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Additionally, these questions can also be used as a framework for evaluating potential candidates for the succession planning and selection process.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Executive compensation has been a source of criticism following a dramatic rise in pay relative to the average worker's wage.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] For example, the relative pay was 20-to-1 in 1965 in the US, but had risen to 376-to-1 by 2000.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The relative pay differs around the world, and, in some smaller countries, is still around 20-to-1.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Observers differ as to whether the rise is due to competition for talent or due to lack of control by compensation committees.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In recent years, investors have demanded more say over executive pay.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Lack of diversity amongst chief executives has also been a source of criticism.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In 2023 the number rose to 10.4% of for Women CEO's of Fortune 500 companies.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Some countries have passed laws mandating boardroom gender quotas.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In 2023 Rockefeller Foundation awarded a grant to Korn Ferry to research strategies and then action a plan to help more women to become CEO's.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] There are contentious claims that a significant number of CEOs have psychopathic tendencies, often characterized by power-seeking behavior and dominance.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] These individuals can often conceal their ruthlessness and antisocial behavior behind a facade of charm and eloquence.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Traits such as courage and risk-taking, generally considered desirable, are often found alongside these psychopathic tendencies.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Tara Swart, a neuroscientist at MIT Sloan School of Management, has suggested that individuals with psychopathic traits thrive in chaotic environments and are aware that others do not.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] As a result, they may intentionally create chaos in the workplace.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] This perspective is explored in the book *Snakes in Suits*, co-authored by Robert D.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] However, Scott Lilienfeld has argued that the attention given to psychopathy in the workplace by both the media and scholars has far exceeded the available scientific evidence.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Emilia Bunea, writing in *Psychology Today*, has linked psychopathic traits in managers to workplace bullying, employee dissatisfaction, and turnover intentions.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Despite this, Bunea cautions that excessive worry about supposed psychopathic managers could discourage individuals from pursuing careers in corporations and deter employees from addressing issues with difficult bosses.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] There have been several notable controversies involving famous CEOs.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Some of the most prominent controversies were a result of the MeToo Movement including Harvey Weinstein and the Weinstein Company, Steve Wynn and Wynn Resorts Ltd., and Leslie Moonves & CBS.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Elon Musk, the CEO of Tesla, Inc. and SpaceX, has been the subject of several controversies.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] In 2018, Musk tweeted "[a]m considering taking Tesla private at $420.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Funding secured" in the middle of a trading day and a few weeks later, Tesla announced it would go private.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] The SEC investigated Musk shortly after his tweet and charged him with securities fraud.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Musk settled the controversy and stepped down as chair of Tesla's board but remained the company's CEO.
[src:business-executive/chief-executive-officer] Musk and Tesla both paid a $20 million penalty to be distributed among harmed investors.
[src:business-executive/companies] A **company** is a legal entity representing an association of legal persons with a shared objective, such as generating profit or benefiting society.
[src:business-executive/companies] Depending on the jurisdiction, companies can take on various forms, including voluntary associations, nonprofit organizations, business entities, financial entities, banks, and educational institutions.
[src:business-executive/companies] Companies have evolved to share common legal features, such as a separate legal personality, limited liability, transferable shares, investor ownership, and a managerial hierarchy.
[src:business-executive/companies] The term "company" may or may not be synonymous with corporation, partnership, firm, or society.
[src:business-executive/companies] Companies are governed by company law, also referred to as corporate law in many regions.
[src:business-executive/companies] Incorporated companies are created through state registration, whereas unincorporated companies are not.
[src:business-executive/companies] When a company closes, it may undergo liquidation to settle its affairs and terminate its legal obligations.
[src:business-executive/companies] Additionally, companies may associate to form corporate groups, which are collections of parent and subsidiary corporations.
[src:business-executive/companies] English law recognised long ago that a corporation would have separate legal personality, also known as corporate personality or juridical personhood.
[src:business-executive/companies] In 1776, Adam Smith wrote in the *Wealth of Nations* that mass corporate activity could not match private entrepreneurship, because people in charge of "other people's money" would not exercise as much care as they would with their own.
[src:business-executive/companies] In 1843, William Gladstone took chairmanship of a Parliamentary Committee on Joint Stock Companies, which led to the Joint Stock Companies Act 1844.
[src:business-executive/companies] At the end of the 19th century in the United States, the law allowed for the concentration of wealth and power in the hands of a few people, or a single person.
[src:business-executive/companies] In response, the Sherman Antitrust Act of 1890 was created to break up big business conglomerates, and the Clayton Act of 1914 gave the government power to halt mergers and acquisitions that could damage the public interest.
[src:business-executive/companies] By the end of the First World War, it was increasingly perceived that ordinary people had little voice compared to the "financial oligarchy" of bankers and industrial magnates.
[src:business-executive/companies] In particular, employees lacked voice compared to shareholders, but plans for a post-war "industrial democracy" (giving employees votes for investing their labor) did not become widespread.
[src:business-executive/companies] The Wall Street crash of 1929 saw the total collapse of stock market values, as shareholders realized that corporations had become overpriced.
[src:business-executive/companies] They sold shares *en masse*, meaning many companies found it hard to get finance.
[src:business-executive/companies] The result was that thousands of businesses were forced to close, and they laid off workers.
[src:business-executive/companies] Because workers had less money to spend, businesses received less income, leading to more closures and lay-offs.
[src:business-executive/companies] This downward spiral began the Great Depression.
[src:business-executive/companies] This led directly to the New Deal reforms of the Securities Act of 1933 and Securities and Exchange Act of 1934.
[src:business-executive/companies] A new Securities and Exchange Commission was empowered to require corporations disclose all material information about their business to the investing public.
[src:business-executive/companies] However, different states had different corporate laws.
[src:business-executive/companies] To increase revenue from corporate tax, individual states had an incentive to lower their standards in a "race to the bottom" to attract corporations to set up their headquarters in the state, particularly where directors controlled the decision to incorporate.
[src:business-executive/companies] "Charter competition", by the 1960s, had led Delaware to become home to the majority of the largest US corporations.
[src:business-executive/companies] This meant that the case law of the Delaware Chancery and Supreme Court became increasingly influential.
[src:business-executive/companies] During the 1980s, a huge takeover and merger boom decreased directors' accountability.
[src:business-executive/companies] To fend off a takeover, courts allowed boards to institute "poison pills" or "shareholder rights plans", which allowed directors to veto any bid – and probably get a payout for letting a takeover happen.
[src:business-executive/companies] More and more people's retirement savings were being invested into the stock market, through pension funds, life insurance and mutual funds.
[src:business-executive/companies] This resulted in a vast growth in the asset management industry, which tended to take control of voting rights.
[src:business-executive/companies] Both the financial sector's share of income, and executive pay for chief executive officers began to rise far beyond real wages for the rest of the workforce.
[src:business-executive/companies] The Enron scandal of 2001 led to some reforms in the Sarbanes-Oxley Act (on separating auditors from consultancy work).
[src:business-executive/companies] The 2008 financial crisis led to minor changes in the Dodd-Frank Act (on soft regulation of pay, alongside derivative markets).
[src:business-executive/companies] However, the basic shape of corporate law in the United States has remained the same since the 1980s.
[src:business-executive/companies] A company can be defined as an "artificial person", invisible, intangible, created by or under law, with a discrete legal capacity (or "personality"), perpetual succession, and a common seal.
[src:business-executive/companies] Except for some senior positions, companies remain unaffected by the death, insanity, or insolvency of an individual member.
[src:business-executive/companies] The English word, "*company*", has its origins in the Old French term *compagnie* (first recorded in 1150), meaning "society, friendship, intimacy; body of soldiers", which came from the Late Latin word *companio* ("one who eats bread with you"), first attested in the Salic law (c.
[src:business-executive/companies] AD 500) as a calque of the Germanic expression *gahlaibo* (literally, "with bread"), related to Old High German *galeipo* ("companion") and to Gothic *gahlaiba* ("messmate").
[src:business-executive/companies] By 1303, the word company referred to trade guilds.
[src:business-executive/companies] The usage of the term *company* to mean "business association" was first recorded in the 1550s, and the abbreviation "co." dates from 1769.
[src:business-executive/companies] In English law, a company is a body corporate or corporation company registered under the Companies Acts or under similar legislation.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] A **government agency** or **state agency**, also known as an **appointed commission**, is a permanent or semi-permanent organization in the machinery of government (bureaucracy) that is responsible for the oversight and administration of specific functions, such as an administration.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] There is a notable variety of agency types.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Although usage differs, a government agency is normally distinct both from a department or ministry, and other types of public body established by government.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The functions of an agency are normally executive in character since different types of organizations (*such as commissions*) are most often constituted in an advisory role — this distinction is often blurred in practice however, it is not allowed.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] A government agency may be established by either a national government or a state government within a federal system.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Agencies can be established by legislation or by executive powers.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The autonomy, independence, and accountability of government agencies also vary widely.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Early examples of organizations that would now be termed a government agency include the British Navy Board, responsible for ships and supplies, which was established in 1546 by King Henry VIII and the British Commissioners of Bankruptcy established in 1570.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] From 1933, the New Deal saw growth in U.S. federal agencies, the "alphabet agencies" as they were used to deliver new programs created by legislation, such as the Federal Emergency Relief Administration.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] From the 1980s, as part of New Public Management, several countries including Australia and the United Kingdom developed the use of agencies to improve efficiency in public services.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Administrative law in France refers to *autorité administrative indépendante* (AAI) or Independent Administrative Authorities.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Independent Administrative Authorities in France may not be instructed or ordered to take specific actions by the government.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The General Secretariat for Macedonia and Thrace (Greek: Γενική Γραμματεία Μακεδονίας-Θράκης), previously Ministry for Macedonia and Thrace (Greek: Υπουργείο Μακεδονίας-Θράκης) is a government agency of the Hellenic Republic that is responsible for the Greek regions of Macedonia and Thrace.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The term *agency* in India has several meanings; for example, the Cabinet and the parliament Secretariat describes itself as a "*nodal agency* for coordination amongst the ministries of the Govt. of India".
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] In the Netherlands, an agency (*agentschap*) is a part of a government ministry with its own management, budget, and financial administration, separate from the ministry to which it belongs.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The minister retains full control of an agency and has full ministerial responsibility for its activities.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Russia has had many government agencies throughout its history.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Today, Russian government agencies such as the FSB, FSO, and the GRU use Spetsnaz or other masked operators for any missions.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Other organizations include Kremlin and presidential security.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The Government agencies in Sweden are State controlled organizations who act independently to carry out the policies of the Government of Sweden.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The Ministries are relatively small and merely policy-making organizations, allowed to control agencies by policy decisions but not by direct orders.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] This means that while the agencies are subject to decisions made by the Government, Ministers are explicitly prohibited (so-called ban on *ministerstyre*) from interfering with the day-to-day operation in an agency or the outcome in individual cases as well.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] In addition to the State and its agencies, there are also local government agencies, which are extensions of municipalities and county councils.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Agencies in the United Kingdom are either executive agencies answerable to government ministers or non-departmental public bodies answerable directly to parliament or the devolved assemblies of the United Kingdom.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] They are also commonly known as Quangos.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Agencies can be created by enabling legislation by the Parliament of the United Kingdom, Scottish Parliament or the Welsh Parliament.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The Congress and President of the United States delegate specific authority to government agencies to regulate the complex facets of the modern American federal state.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Also, most of the 50 U.S. states have created similar government agencies.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Each state government is similar to the national government, with all but one having a bicameral legislature.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The term "government agency" or "administrative agency" usually applies to one of the independent agencies of the United States federal government, which exercise some degree of independence from the President's control.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Although the heads of independent agencies are often appointed by the government, they can usually be removed only for cause.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The heads of independent agencies work together in groups, such as a commission, board or council.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Independent agencies often function as miniature versions of the tripartite federal government with the authority to legislate (through the issuing or promulgation of regulations), to adjudicate disputes, and to enforce agency regulations.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Examples of independent agencies include the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), Federal Reserve Board, U.S.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), the National Labor Relations Board (NLRB) and the Federal Trade Commission (FTC).
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] A broader definition of the term "government agency" also means the United States federal executive departments that include the President's cabinet-level departments and their sub-units.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Examples of these include the Department of Energy (DOE) and the Internal Revenue Service (IRS), which is a bureau of the Department of the Treasury.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Most federal agencies are created by Congress through "organic statutes," which define the scope of their authority.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] Because the Constitution does not expressly mention federal agencies, some commentators have called agencies the "headless fourth branch" of the federal government.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] However, most independent agencies are technically part of the executive branch, while others work within the legislative branch.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] By enacting the Administrative Procedure Act (APA) in 1946, Congress established means to oversee agency action through uniform administrative law procedures for setting regulations and adjudicating claims.
[src:business-executive/government-agencies] The APA also establishes judicial review of agency action.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] IERG accumulates and distributes expertise and information related to the conduct of global business.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] IERG members have extensive international experience.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] To join the organization, a prospect must demonstrate that he or she has worked for three or more years in a market outside his country of origin.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] Membership is only by invitation and sponsorship, and application is followed by a screening interview.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] Most members are fluent in two or more languages.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] Members have lived, or now live, in all major geographical or geo-political regions, including Abu Dhabi, Australia, Bangladesh, Brazil, China, Denmark, France, Germany, Hong Kong, Hungary, India, Japan, the Netherlands, Singapore, South Korea, Switzerland, United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] In addition, prospective members must have held an executive level position.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] Current IERG members include CEOs, CFOs, CIOs, CMOs, and division presidents from both large and small companies.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] IERG encourages senior executives and business people from all functional specializations and a broad range of industries to join.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] Current members come from the auto industry, energy, banking, financial services, insurance, advertising, fast-moving consumer goods, mining, information technology, and many other industries.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] According to a recent survey of members, almost 40% of members joined 7 or more years ago.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] IERG is governed by a Board of Directors.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] Many of its routine activities are organized by members who volunteer their time.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] Member-led special interest groups (SIGs) operate across industries and geographic boundaries.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] The Princeton Executive Network (PEN), an association of senior executives living or working within commuting distance of Princeton, NJ, welcomes IERG members to its normally invitation-only meetings.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] The British American Business Council (BOAC, www.babcoc.org) of Orange County, CA welcomes participation of IERG members to its invitation-only functions.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] IERG organizes monthly meetings for its members through each of its chapters.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] In addition, IERG presents periodic webinars on subjects related to international business, including discussion of current trends in trade, economic and political policy, and multicultural communications.
[src:business-executive/international-executive-resources-group] IERG periodically invites accomplished professionals and distinguished personalities (Chairmen, CEOs, authors, and thought leaders) as guest speakers.
